groups of patients. Many of the epileptic seizures presented in these patients 
are generally of the acute symptomatic type; they therefore require no long-term 
antiepileptic treatment and have a good prognosis, once the situation or disease 
that triggers them is righted or treated. When it comes to choosing a possible 
antiepileptic drug for these patients, basically all the pharmacological 
treatments for these medical diseases must be considered. This is because of the 
possible interactions that may reciprocally alter the effectiveness of the two 
types of drugs and, similarly, their pharmacokinetics, pharmacodynamic behaviour 
and preferred choice of pathways.

