Effects of physical therapy intervention for children with acute lymphoblastic 
leukemia.

Marchese VG(1), Chiarello LA, Lange BJ.

Author information:
(1)Department of Rehabilitation Services, St. Jude Children's Research Hospital, 
Tennessee, USA. victoria.marchese@stjude.org

BACKGROUND: The purpose of this study was to examine the effects of physical 
therapy intervention in children with acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL).
PROCEDURE: Twenty-eight children aged 4-15 years were randomly assigned to an 
intervention or control group. The intervention group received five sessions of 
physical therapy and was instructed to perform an individualized home exercise 
program consisting of ankle dorsiflexion stretching, lower extremity 
strengthening, and aerobic exercise.
RESULTS: After 4 months children who received physical therapy intervention had 
significantly improved ankle dorsiflexion active range of motion and knee 
extension strength (P < 0.01). Differences were not found between the two groups 
for any of the other dependent variables.
CONCLUSIONS: Physical therapy intervention for children with ALL receiving 
maintenance chemotherapy improved two body functions important for normal gait. 
Physical therapy programs initiated earlier in treatment and with greater 
emphasis on endurance activities may also improve stamina and quality of life 
(QOL).

